se of this reality, we were averaging one support ticket/thread for every c=
ouple sales, which amounts to a ton of time spent on support. Too much time=
 for two people. For a little comparison, we average less than one support =
ticket/thread per 15-20 customers for my <a href=3D"https://usefathom.com/"=
 style=3D"color:#f9415d!important;font-weight:600!important;text-decoration=
:underline;font-family:-apple-system,BlinkMacSystemFont,San Francisco,Helve=
tica Neue,Helvetica,Ubuntu,Roboto,Noto,Segoe UI,Arial,sans-serif!important;=
letter-spacing:-0.007em!important;line-height:1.6!important" target=3D"_bla=
nk">Fathom Analytics</a> product (stand-alone SaaS app), and those tickets =
don&#39;t typically require debugging an entire website or group of plugins=
. Actually, more than half our support tickets are either business developm=
ent questions or feature requests (both are easy to deal with).</p>

<p dir=3D"ltr" style=3D"margin:10px 0;padding:0;margin-bottom:20px;color:#1=
11!important;font-family:-apple-system,BlinkMacSystemFont,San Francisco,Hel=
vetica Neue,Helvetica,Ubuntu,Roboto,Noto,Segoe UI,Arial,sans-serif!importan=
t;font-size:17px;line-height:1.6!important;text-align:left;letter-spacing:-=
0.007em!important">A tiny company (or &quot;company of one&quot; if you&#39=
;d like) isn&#39;t set up to handle that scale of support. Support scaled s=
o close to revenue increases. Whereas a larger company, like the one we sol=
d the product to, has a dedicated support team and has baked into their com=
pany infrastructure a way to deal with large volumes of support for large v=
olumes of sales. They excel at being an operator company. This is why we so=
ld to them - obviously we get a payout, but moreso, we only wanted to sell =
to a company who could on day-one take over support and eventually make sup=
port even better than we could.</p>

